# RAXE Suppression File (.raxeignore)
#
# This file allows you to suppress false positive detections from RAXE scans.
# Similar to .gitignore, it uses pattern matching to suppress specific rules.
#
# Format: <pattern>  # <reason>
#
# Patterns support wildcards:
#   - pi-*          : Matches all prompt injection rules (pi-001, pi-002, etc.)
#   - *-injection   : Matches all injection-related rules
#   - pi-00*        : Matches pi-001, pi-002, etc.
#   - jb-regex-*    : Matches all jailbreak regex rules
#
# Examples:

# ============================================================================
# Suppress specific rules by exact ID
# ============================================================================

# False positive in our documentation examples
# pi-001  # Instruction patterns appear in code examples

# Too sensitive for our knowledge base content
# jb-regex-basic  # Common phrases in support documentation

# Known safe pattern in our codebase
# cmd-injection-001  # CLI argument parsing uses expected patterns


# ============================================================================
# Suppress entire rule families
# ============================================================================

# Disable all prompt injection detection (NOT RECOMMENDED for production)
# pi-*  # Disable all prompt injection rules

# Disable all jailbreak detection
# jb-*  # Disable all jailbreak rules

# Disable all PII detection
# pii-*  # Disable all PII detection rules


# ============================================================================
# Suppress specific sub-families
# ============================================================================

# Disable regex-based jailbreak detection
# jb-regex-*  # Regex jailbreak rules too sensitive

# Disable all injection detection (PI, CMD, etc.)
# *-injection  # All injection detection rules


# ============================================================================
# Temporary suppressions (use --expires flag in CLI)
# ============================================================================

# Suppress during migration period
# pi-advanced-001  # Temporary: migrating to new prompt template

# Suppress while investigating
# pii-email  # Investigating false positives in email validation


# ============================================================================
# Context-specific suppressions
# ============================================================================

# Safe in testing environment
# jb-dan-prompt  # DAN prompts used in testing/red-teaming

# Expected in code review comments
# pi-system-override  # Code review uses system override examples


# ============================================================================
# BEST PRACTICES
# ============================================================================
#
# 1. Always provide a reason - helps with audit trail
# 2. Be specific - suppress individual rules when possible
# 3. Review regularly - suppressions can hide real threats
# 4. Use expiration dates - temporary fixes shouldn't be permanent
# 5. Document context - why is this pattern safe in your use case?
# 6. Audit suppressions - use `raxe suppress audit` to review
#
